Trump and the Economy
New York — Financial markets finally woke up, realizing that Trump is the President of the United States.
The world has endured the unfiltered tweets and public statements from this most powerful person on the globe for two years. The obvious question is, what has kept this going for so long?
On one hand, up until now, investors have been treating Trump as a talker who doesn't follow through.
As long as he implements tax cuts, deregulation, and other policies favorable to the corporate sector and shareholders, they are willing to give him the benefit of the doubt.
Many believe that eventually, "the adult in the room" will rein in Trump and ensure that government policies stay within bounds.
This assumption was at least partly confirmed during Trump's first year in office, a period during which economic growth and expectations of corporate profit growth — thanks to the upcoming tax cuts and deregulation — led to strong stock market performance.
In 2017, U.S. stock indexes rose by more than 20%.
But in 2018, the situation turned sharply downward, especially in the last few months.
Although corporate profits increased by more than 20% (thanks to tax cuts), the U.S. stock market fluctuated for most of the year and then plunged sharply.
Currently, various indexes are in a correction phase (i.e., down 10% from their recent highs), with tech indexes (such as the NASDAQ) having fallen into a bear market (down 20% or more).
Although increased market volatility reflects concerns about China, Italy, and other eurozone economies, as well as key emerging economies, the recent turbulence is due to Trump.
At the start of the year, Trump implemented reckless tax cuts, which pushed up long-term interest rates and pushed an economy already near full employment to its peak.
By February, concerns about inflation rising above the Federal Reserve's target of 2% triggered the first flight-to-safety rush of 2018.
Then, Trump launched a trade war against China and other important U.S. trade partners.
Concerns about government protectionist policies have fluctuated throughout the year but are now reaching new heights.
Recent actions by the U.S. toward China seem to be preparing for a comprehensive trade, economic, and geopolitical cold war.
Another concern is that Trump's other policies may lead to stagflation (slower growth, while inflation rises).
After all, Trump is preparing to restrict the inflow of foreign direct investment and has implemented extensive immigration restrictions, which will hinder the growth of labor supply in the context of an increasingly serious aging population and skill mismatch.
In addition, the Trump administration has yet to propose a stimulus plan for boosting private-sector productivity or accelerating the transition to a green economy through infrastructure initiatives.
On Twitter and other occasions, Trump has continually criticized companies' hiring, production, investment, and pricing behaviors, especially technology companies, which have already faced widespread opposition and increasingly intense competition from Chinese rivals.
Emerging markets have also been affected by U.S. policies.
Fiscal stimulus and monetary policy tightening have raised both short-term and long-term interest rates, strengthening the dollar.
As a result, emerging economies have experienced capital outflows and rising values of dollar-denominated debt.
Emerging economies that heavily rely on exports have suffered losses due to falling commodity prices, and even countries with only indirect trade ties with China have felt the impact of the trade war.
The very oil policies of Trump have also created volatility.
The U.S. reimposing sanctions on Iran raised oil prices, and afterward, the U.S. government revoked exemptions and pressured Saudi Arabia to increase oil production, causing oil prices to plummet.
Although American consumers benefited from low oil prices, energy company stock prices could not withstand the pressure.
Furthermore, excessive oil price volatility is detrimental to both producers and consumers, as it hinders informed investment and consumption decisions.
Worse still, now it is clear that almost all the benefits from the previous year's tax cuts have flowed to the corporate sector, rather than to households in the form of higher real (inflation-adjusted) wages.
This means that household consumption may soon slow down, further affecting the economy.
However, the main reason for the recent sharp decline in U.S. and global stock markets in the last quarter is Trump's own remarks and actions.
Worse than the prominent risk of a full-scale trade war with China (although he recently reached a "truce" with Chinese President Xi Jinping) is Trump's public attack on the Federal Reserve. His attacks began in the spring of 2018, when the U.S. economic growth rate exceeded 4%.
Due to these earlier attacks, the market became skittish when the Federal Reserve correctly decided to raise interest rates this month and hinted at a slower rate hike in 2019.
More likely, the relatively hawkish stance of the Federal Reserve is a response to Trump's attacks on it.
Facing hostile presidential tweets, Federal Reserve Chair Jerome Powell needs to send a signal that the central bank still maintains political independence.
But then, because Congress refused to fund his useless border wall with Mexico, Trump decided to shut down part of the federal government.
This move put the market into a state of near panic, as reports soon emerged that Trump wanted to fire Powell — which could turn a market correction into a crash.
Just before the Christmas holiday, U.S. Treasury Secretary Steven Mnuchin was forced to make a public statement to calm the market.
He claimed that Trump had no plan to fire Powell, and that the U.S. fiscal situation was good — but this恰恰 highlights the question of whether the situation is truly good.
And the recent changes in government personnel, which may not affect economic decisions, have also caused market concerns.
The Chief of Staff John Kelly and Defense Secretary James Mattis are about to leave, and the Trump administration will no longer have any sane individuals.
The remaining officials will all be economic nationalists and hardliners in foreign policy, following Trump's lead.
The possibility of all-out geopolitical confrontation with China remains uneliminated.
A new Cold War is likely to lead to deglobalization and disrupt global supply chains, but the technology sector will be the first to suffer, as evidenced by the recent ZTE and Huawei cases.
Meanwhile, Trump seems determined to undermine the cohesion of the EU and NATO during a time of economic and political instability in Europe.
The special prosecutor Robert Mueller's investigation into Trump's 2016 campaign's ties to Russia serves as the Damocles sword over Trump's presidency.
Trump is now the Dr. Strangelove of financial markets.
Like the paranoid madman in Stanley Kubrick's classic film, he is trapped in a mutually assured economic destruction.
Now, the market sees this danger, and the risks of a financial crisis and global recession are rising.
